  "text": "The AS is sensing the spectrum in order to perform reactive jamming, e.g., to jam BPSK modulated waveforms that are part of traffic signaling (preambles, control-plane packets), which if corrupted makes the rest of communication meaningless. Note that many preambles are BPSK-modulated, as well as the packets in the control plane of most protocols (such as acknowledgments), and if the they get corrupted by jamming the whole data packet is lost [CITATION_1] . Hence, the DLA would want to create the AdEx that disguises BPSK as QPSK (or other) to avoid the EW attack by the DL-based reactive jammer (i.e., AS) [CITATION_2] . Note that reactive jamming is very difficult to detect [CITATION_3] , but it heavily relies on the inference based on spectrum sensing. If the inference is adversarially attacked, the jammer will be mitigated (by failing to reactively transmit a jamming signal). We here take the side of the jammer in attempting to detect such adversarial attacks.",
